53    /**
54    * CommandLineRunner translates flags into Java API calls on the Compiler.
55    *
56    * This class may be extended and used to create other Java classes
57    * that behave the same as running the Compiler from the command line. If you
58    * want to run the compiler in-process in Java, you should look at this class
59    * for hints on what API calls to make, but you should not use this class
60    * directly.
61    *
62    * Example:
63    * <pre>
64    * class MyCommandLineRunner extends CommandLineRunner {
65    * MyCommandLineRunner(String[] args) {
66    * super(args);
67    * }
68    *
69    * {@code @Override} protected CompilerOptions createOptions() {
70    * CompilerOptions options = super.createOptions();
71    * addMyCrazyCompilerPassThatOutputsAnExtraFile(options);
72    * return options;
73    * }
74    *
75    * public static void main(String[] args) {
76    * MyCommandLineRunner runner = new MyCommandLineRunner(args);
77    * if (runner.shouldRunCompiler()) {
78    * runner.run();
79    * } else {
80    * System.exit(-1);
81    * }
82    * }
83    * }
84    * </pre>
85    *
86    * This class is totally not thread-safe.
87    *
88    * @author bolinfest@google.com (Michael Bolin)
89    */
 
57.8% Uncovered Elements: 73 (173) Complexity: 38 Complexity Density: 0.32

423    * Closure Compiler in combination with {@code find} and {@code xargs}:
424    * <pre>

426    * | xargs java -jar compiler.jar --manage_closure_dependencies
